As pointed out by Ref.25, the whitewater rivers in the Andean-foreland basin—Ucayali, Huallaga, Beni and Maranon—are highly dynamic due to the high suspended sediment load they carry (0.23 ± 0.16 Mt/year). In fact, the suspended load in these catchments was found to be positively correlated with river migration rates37 because sediment transport increases the buildup of fluvial bars, which enhances the topographic steering of longitudinal flow38 and thus promotes shear stress and bank erosion39. Such a key phenomenon, combined with the nutrient-rich sediment and high biomass density (8–16 GgC/km2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
